#Text=I
#Text=THEY had four hours in New York between trains .
#Text=The one thing Babbitt wished to see was the Pennsylvania Hotel , which had been built since his last visit .
#Text=He stared up at it , muttering , “ Twenty-two hundred rooms and twenty-two hundred baths !
#Text=That 's got everything in the world beat .
#Text=Lord , their turnover must be --
#Text=well , suppose price of rooms is four to eight dollars a day , and I suppose maybe some ten and --
#Text=four times twenty-two hundred-say six times twenty-two hundred --
#Text=well , anyway , with restaurants and everything , say summers between eight and fifteen thousand a day .
#Text=Every day !
#Text=I never thought I 'd see a thing like that !
#Text=Some town !
#Text=Of course the average fellow in Zenith has got more Individual Initiative than the fourflushers here , but I got to hand it to New York .
#Text=Yes , sir , town , you 're all right -- some ways .
#Text=Well , old Paulski , I guess we 've seen everything that 's worth while .
#Text=How 'll we kill the rest of the time ?
#Text=Movie ? ”
#Text=But Paul desired to see a liner .
#Text=“ Always wanted to go to Europe -- and , by thunder , I will , too , some day before I past out , ” he sighed .
#Text=From a rough wharf on the North River they stared at the stern of the Aquitania and her stacks and wireless antenna lifted above the dock-house which shut her in .
#Text=“ By golly , ” Babbitt droned , “ would n't be so bad to go over to the Old Country and take a squint at all these ruins , and the place where Shakespeare was born .
#Text=And think of being able to order a drink whenever you wanted one !
#Text=Just range up to a bar and holler out loud , ' Gimme a cocktail , and darn the police ! '
#Text=Not bad at all .
#Text=What juh like to see , over there , Paulibus ? ”
#Text=Paul did not answer .
#Text=Babbitt turned .
#Text=Paul was standing with clenched fists , head drooping , staring at the liner as in terror .
#Text=His thin body , seen against the summer-glaring planks of the wharf , was childishly meager .
#Text=Again , “ What would you hit for on the other side , Paul ? ”
#Text=Scowling at the steamer , his breast heaving , Paul whispered , “ Oh , my God ! ”
#Text=While Babbitt watched him anxiously he snapped , “ Come on , let 's get out of this , ” and hastened down the wharf , not looking back .
#Text=“ That 's funny , ” considered Babbitt .
#Text=“ The boy did n't care for seeing the ocean boats after all .
#Text=I thought he 'd be interested in ' em . ”
#Text=II

#Text=Though he exulted , and made sage speculations about locomotive horse-power , as their train climbed the Maine mountain-ridge and from the summit he looked down the shining way among the pines ; though he remarked , “ Well , by golly ! ”

#Text=when he discovered that the station at Katadumcook , the end of the line , was an aged freight-car ; Babbitt 's moment of impassioned release came when they sat on a tiny wharf on Lake Sunasquam , awaiting the launch from the hotel .
#Text=A raft had floated down the lake ; between the logs and the shore , the water was transparent , thin-looking , flashing with minnows .
#Text=A guide in black felt hat with trout-flies in the band , and flannel shirt of a peculiarly daring blue , sat on a log and whittled and was silent .
#Text=A dog , a good country dog , black and woolly gray , a dog rich in leisure and in meditation , scratched and grunted and slept .

#Text=The thick sunlight was lavish on the bright water , on the rim of gold-green balsam boughs , the silver birches and tropic ferns , and across the lake it burned on the sturdy shoulders of the mountains .
#Text=Over everything was a holy peace .
#Text=Silent , they loafed on the edge of the wharf , swinging their legs above the water .
#Text=The immense tenderness of the place sank into Babbitt , and he murmured , “ I 'd just like to sit here -- the rest of my life -- and whittle -- and sit .
#Text=And never hear a typewriter .
#Text=Or Stan Graff fussing in the ' phone .
#Text=Or Rone and Ted scrapping .
#Text=Just sit .
#Text=Gosh ! ”
#Text=He patted Paul 's shoulder .
#Text=“ How does it strike you , old snoozer ? ”
#Text=“ Oh , it 's darn good , Georgie .
#Text=There 's something sort of eternal about it . ”
#Text=For once , Babbitt understood him .
#Text=III

#Text=Their launch rounded the bend ; at the head of the lake , under a mountain slope , they saw the little central dining-shack of their hotel and the crescent of squat log cottages which served as bedrooms .
#Text=They landed , and endured the critical examination of the habitues who had been at the hotel for a whole week .
#Text=In their cottage , with its high stone fireplace , they hastened , as Babbitt expressed it , to “ get into some regular he-togs . ”
#Text=They came out ; Paul in an old gray suit and soft white shirt ; Babbitt in khaki shirt and vast and flapping khaki trousers .
#Text=It was excessively new khaki ; his rimless spectacles belonged to a city office ; and his face was not tanned but a city pink .
#Text=He made a discordant noise in the place .
#Text=But with infinite satisfaction he slapped his legs and crowed , “ Say , this is getting back home , eh ? ”
#Text=They stood on the wharf before the hotel .
#Text=He winked at Paul and drew from his back pocket a plug of chewing-tobacco , a vulgarism forbidden in the Babbitt home .
#Text=He took a chew , beaming and wagging his head as he tugged at it .
#Text=“ Um !
#Text=Um !
#Text=Maybe I have n't been hungry for a wad of eating-tobacco !
#Text=Have some ? ”
#Text=They looked at each other in a grin of understanding .
#Text=Paul took the plug , gnawed at it .
#Text=They stood quiet , their jaws working .
#Text=They solemnly spat , one after the other , into the placid water .
#Text=They stretched voluptuously , with lifted arms and arched backs .
#Text=From beyond the mountains came the shuffling sound of a far-off train .
#Text=A trout leaped , and fell back in a silver circle .
#Text=They sighed together .
